hanging up is way too cheap on them :-P <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gyreredbranch>Gyre Redbranch</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 277<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/16/03 7:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4047.topic&index=9>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: well</span><hr size=1> In my lawyer days, I represented some credit-reporting agencies and one bill collection company.  Don't jump on me -- I stopped doing all of that <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   The below is offered in the event that it may be helpful.<br>
<br>
They have to ask if you're his spouse.  No option -- they have to.  The Federal Fair Debt Collections Practices Act constrains what bill collectors can say to whom.  One of the major prohibitions in the act is telling people why you are trying to reach the debtor, or even that the call is from a bill collector.  There is an exception for the debtor's spouse -- they CAN talk to the spouse (although they cannot ask the spouse to pay, unless it was a joint account).  If they don't know you're the spouse, even leaving the name of their company can get them in trouble.<br>
<br>
From the bill collector's standpoint, it's quite necessary to follow this rule.  The penalties for breaking it can be significant, and liability attaches not only to the company, but to the actual individual making the call.  For some schlub making US$ 20,000 per year, a $5,000 fine would mean bankruptcy.<br>
<br>
Now, we all realise it's odd, rude and contrary to the normal conventions of telephonic contact to call someone, then ask who THEY are.  But that's what the law requires in this case.<br>
<br>
Please note that this act does not apply to the original creditor (just to cut off replies that point out that companies like Providian will certainly call and tell whoever answers the phone that so-and-so owes them money).<br>
<br>
If you don't want them to call again, you can stop it.  Ask for their address.  Have your husband write them and say &quot;Never call me again, anywhere.&quot;  That stops them.  You can even stop mail contact with a cease and desist request (just mail them a letter saying &quot;Stop contacting us completely&quot;).  Know that this can be risky.  If the amount is large enough, they'll forward it to a lawyer for action.<br>
<br>
Heh, I don't know anything about you.  This could well be mistaken identity, or some crap related to a card your husband paid off 10 years ago, but somebody didn't update their records.  So PLEASE IGNORE ALL OF THIS if it's not applicable.  I'm trying to offer a bit of explanation, not offend you or imply anything negative <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Heck, I had an agency chasing me a few years ago, for a card I cancelled in 1989.<br>
<br>
I also don't mean to imply that bill collectors are all wonderful people who are simply following the law.  All industries have a mix of good folks, normal folks and complete rat-bastards.  Bill collection certainly collects a disproportionate share of the latter category.<br>
<br>
 <p>Hunter Gyre Redbranch<br>

