<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://kerryandtom.blog-city.com">... has anyone seen my marbles? ...</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rathmorg>Rathmorg</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 56<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/16/03 10:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4047.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: well</span><hr size=1> You can download a tone to record onto your answering machine that imitates the tone you phone makes if it were diconnected.  Or you can buy a device that does the same thing.  When the computer that called you hears this tone, it hangs up and deletes your number from its database since it thinks your phone is diconnected and a waste of resourses to call again.<br>
<br>
Pro: Download free.  Cons: If answering machine is set to 4 rings.  And you have to record the sound as the first thing on your outgoing message.<br>
<br>
Pro: Device works as soon as you pick up the phone.  Cons: You hear the sound.  Costs around 20 bucks.<br>
<br>
The only other factor is that this only works when a computer makes the call.  If it's a human, they will still try to talk after the short beep.<br>
<br>
I have the device and have eliminated roughly 90% of unwanted telemarketers calls. <br>
<br>
